            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Shannon Riley is a product of a San Francisco that feels, to her, like a sepia-toned photograph. Born and raised in the Outer Sunset, she\u2019s the daughter of a firefighter and a school secretary. Her childhood was marked by foggy mornings, the roar of the ocean from four blocks away, and the comforting predictability of a working-class neighborhood. College was a distant concept, a luxury her family couldn\u2019t entertain, especially after her father took an early retirement due to a back injury. Shannon graduated from high school, handed her diploma to her proud parents, and started working the next Monday.\n\nHer twenties were a patchwork of service jobs\u2014barista, rental car agent, delivery driver. Each paid the bills but felt like a temporary stop. The turning point came a decade ago when she landed a job as a corporate shuttle operator. The stability, benefits, and predictable hours were a godsend. Now, she spends her days navigating the city\u2019s arteries in a state-of-the-art, air-conditioned bus, a vessel for the tech industry that has reshaped her hometown. From her driver's seat, she is a silent observer of a world she is not part of, ferrying young engineers who discuss stock options and IPOs.\n\nDivorced in her early thirties, Shannon\u2019s life is now one of routine and quiet self-reliance. Her day starts at 5:00 a.m. in the small, rent-controlled apartment she's had for fifteen years. After her 8.5-mile commute to the depot in South of Market, she\u2019s on the road, her solitude punctuated only by a classic rock station and the muffled chatter of her passengers. Her social life is small but solid: weekly dinners with her parents, who still live in her childhood home, and Friday beers with a few old high school friends at a no-frills neighborhood bar.\n\nShannon\u2019s dreams are pragmatic. She doesn\u2019t aspire to wealth, but to security. Her deepest hope is to one day save enough for a down payment on a small condo, a permanent anchor in the city that is actively trying to price her out. She loves San Francisco with the fierce, complicated loyalty of a native, even as she feels like a ghost haunting its new, gleaming facade. Each day, she drives its future forward, holding on tightly to its past."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers being seven, her father\u2019s hand swallowing hers as they walked to the Great Highway during a winter storm. The wind whipped sand that stung her cheeks, and the ocean was a furious, gray monster. He stood with her, solid as the seawall, just watching the waves crash. She wasn\u2019t scared; she was in awe. Next to him, facing that raw power, she felt like the safest person in the world. It was the day she learned San Francisco\u2019s beauty had teeth, and she loved it for that.\n\n2.\nThe day after graduation, she placed her diploma, still in its cheap vinyl folder, on the living room mantel. Her mom cried quietly, and her dad, his back already a constant source of pain, gave a firm, proud nod. There was no talk of college parties or moving into a dorm. It was a moment of quiet finality. The diploma wasn\u2019t a key unlocking the future; it was a certificate of completion. This chapter was over. The next, her working life, began on Monday. That acceptance settled deep in her bones.\n\n3.\nThe first morning after her husband left, she woke to an unnerving silence. For years, his breathing had been the first sound of her day. Now, there was only the distant hum of the N Judah. She lay there, staring at the empty side of the bed, and felt not grief, but a startling sense of space. It was a blank page. The quiet wasn't an absence, but an opportunity. That morning, in her small apartment, she wasn't lonely; she was simply, and completely, on her own. Self-reliance became her comfort.\n\n4.\nShe was navigating through SoMa traffic when two young men in the front seats started talking about their company\u2019s IPO. One calculated how his options would be enough for a house in Noe Valley, cash. Shannon gripped the wheel, separated by a pane of glass and a billion dollars. It wasn't envy she felt, but a profound, dizzying sense of invisibility. She was the silent, steady hand moving them toward a future she would only ever witness from the driver\u2019s seat. It solidified her place as a ghost in her own city.\n\n5.\nStanding with her friends outside The Gold Cane on its last night felt like a wake. They didn\u2019t talk much, just watched the old neon sign flicker, a beacon for decades of their lives. A rumor said it was being replaced by a minimalist cafe. The loss felt physical, like a rib being removed. It was more than a bar; it was a landmark of her own personal map. That night, her pragmatic dream of a condo became fierce\u2014a desperate need for one permanent spot in a city actively erasing her past."
